{
  "text": "Helicobacter pylori proteomics was started with the aim to understand the protein composition of a bacterium containing a relatively small genome and to find immunologically relevant proteins [CITATION_1] . The genome of the two strains 26695 (2) and J99 [CITATION_2] has been sequenced completely, and gene annotation has revealed about 1,500 genes for each of them. Proteomics using two-dimensional electrophoresis (2-DE) [CITATION_3] resolved about 1,800 spots of cellular proteins of strain 26695 from which 152 were identified by MALDI-MS peptide mass fingerprinting. These spots comprise 126 different proteins, which correspond to 8% of the open reading frames predicted by genomics [CITATION_4] . Data of the H. pylori proteome are available on the World Wide Web (www.mpiib-berlin.mpg.de/2D-PAGE/ EBP-PAGE/index.html).",
  "citation_candidates": [
